The education of children was frequently made the subject of Chrysippea. monographic treatment by the ancients, more particularly hythe Greeks.¹⁹² The originale have unfortunately been entirely lost, or preserved only in meagre and insignificant fragments, but among

these Chrysippos' Περὶ ratior ἀγωγῆς seems to have been the most extensively used. Its popularity was not so much due to any originality of treatment, stylistic charm or profundity of observa tion, for the Stolo Chalcenteros was not distinguished for any of these qualities‚ hut rather to the accumulation of the opinions oi others,¹⁹⁸ which could not but make his compilatione a repository of useful information‚ highly welcome to later writers.
